# Steps to get access from GitHub to K8s (to perform CD-process):
# add 'microservices-account-token' to rbac.yaml (kind: Secret).
minikube kubectl -- apply -f base/rbac.yaml
minikube kubectl -- get secret microservices-account-token -n sample-mcs -o jsonpath='{.data.token}' | base64 --decode
# the above command shows a token (~1000chars)
minikube kubectl -- get secret microservices-account-token -n sample-mcs -o jsonpath='{.data.ca\.crt}' | base64 --decode > ca.crt
# the above command will generate ca.crt file and put it to the folder, from where you run this command (e.g.: x_k8s).
# the below command gets APIâ€‘endpoint minikube (example -> https://127.0.0.1:6443 or other port)
minikube kubectl -- config view --minify -o jsonpath='{.clusters[0].cluster.server}'
# Then, create kubeconfig.yaml (kind: Config) and carefully fill it with previously generated data.
# Keep it separately from the rest manifest files. It should not ne applied by K8s. Only for copying to GitHub.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
links (internals: call m3 from m1 in code):
 http://m3-service.sample-mcs.svc.cluster.local:8080 (if both microservices are NOT in the same NS)
 http://m3-service:8080 (if both microservices are in the same NS)
 http://m3-service (if using @LoadBalancer)
links (externals):
 http://localhost:8501/ui/
 http://127.0.0.1.nip.io/m1/hi
